Resource Manifests (OpenShift / Kubernetes)
Goal
Deploy and update applications using YAML manifest files instead of long commands.
A Resource Manifest is a file that describes a Kubernetes/OpenShift resource.
Example resources:
•	Pod
•	Deployment
•	Service
•	ConfigMap
•	PersistentVolumeClaim
These are written in YAML files.
Example:
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: myapp
spec:
  replicas: 2
________________________________________
Imperative vs Declarative Approach
There are two ways to manage resources in OpenShift.
Method	Meaning
Imperative	Execute commands directly
Declarative	Define desired state in YAML
________________________________________
Imperative Commands
Imperative commands tell Kubernetes what to do immediately.
Example:
oc create deployment myapp --image=nginx
This directly creates a deployment.
Example with more parameters:
oc create deployment db-pod --port 3306 \
--image registry.example.com/mysql
Problem with Imperative
1️⃣ Hard to reproduce
2️⃣ Hard to track changes
3️⃣ No version control
4️⃣ Not good for automation
________________________________________
Declarative Commands
Declarative approach means:
Define the desired state in YAML.
Example manifest:
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: hello-openshift
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: hello-openshift
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: hello-openshift
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: hello
        image: quay.io/redhattraining/hello-world-nginx:v1.0
Apply it with:
oc apply -f deployment.yaml
This creates or updates the deployment.
________________________________________
Why Declarative is Preferred
Advantages:
1. Reproducibility
You can deploy the same application again easily.
2. Version Control
Store YAML in Git.
Example:
github repo
   ├── deployment.yaml
   ├── service.yaml
   └── route.yaml
3. GitOps Support
GitOps tools like:
•	ArgoCD
•	Flux
automatically apply YAML manifests.
4. Easy rollback
Just revert the Git commit.
________________________________________
Imperative Workflow Example
Step-by-step development.
Step 1 Create deployment
oc create deployment db-pod --port 3306 \
--image registry/mysql
Output:
deployment.apps/db-pod created
________________________________________
Step 2 Add environment variables
oc set env deployment/db-pod \
MYSQL_USER=user1 \
MYSQL_PASSWORD=mypa55w0rd \
MYSQL_DATABASE=items
This modifies the deployment.
________________________________________
Step 3 Add other resources
Examples:
Create service
oc expose deployment db-pod --port=3306
Create route
oc expose service db-pod
________________________________________
This is good for development but bad for production.
________________________________________
Creating Manifest Files
Writing YAML manually is slow.
There are three ways to generate YAML.
________________________________________
Method 1: From Web Console
Open resource → YAML tab → copy manifest.
________________________________________
Method 2: Using dry-run
Example:
oc create deployment hello-openshift \
--image quay.io/redhattraining/hello-world-nginx:v1.0 \
-o yaml \
--dry-run=client
Explanation:
Option	Meaning
-o yaml	output YAML
--dry-run=client	don't create resource
Output example:
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: hello-openshift
spec:
  replicas: 1
________________________________________
Save YAML to file
oc create deployment hello-openshift \
--image nginx \
-o yaml \
--dry-run=client > deployment.yaml
________________________________________
Manifest Structure
Every Kubernetes manifest has four main sections.
apiVersion
kind
metadata
spec
Example:
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: hello-openshift
spec:
  replicas: 2
________________________________________
Important Deployment Fields
Namespace
metadata:
  namespace: resource-manifests
Ensures resource is created in correct project.
________________________________________
Replicas
replicas: 2
Number of pods.
________________________________________
Container Image
containers:
- name: nginx
  image: nginx:latest
Defines container.
________________________________________
Container Port
ports:
- containerPort: 8080
Port exposed by container.
________________________________________
Multiple Resources in One YAML
You can put multiple resources in one file.
Separator:
---
Example:
---
kind: Deployment
...
---
kind: Service
...
________________________________________
Deploying Manifests
Create resources
oc create -f deployment.yaml
________________________________________
Create resources from directory
oc create -f my-app/
________________________________________
Recursive directory
oc create -R -f my-app/
Meaning:
•	Process all YAML files
•	Include subdirectories
________________________________________
Updating Resources
Instead of create, we use:
oc apply
Example:
oc apply -f deployment.yaml
This:
1.	Creates resource if it doesn't exist
2.	Updates resource if it exists
________________________________________
How oc apply Works
It compares:
1️⃣ Manifest file
2️⃣ Current cluster state
3️⃣ Last applied configuration
Annotation used:
kubectl.kubernetes.io/last-applied-configuration
This helps Kubernetes track configuration changes.
________________________________________
Validating YAML Before Applying
Always validate YAML.
Command:
oc apply -f deployment.yaml \
--dry-run=server --validate=true
Meaning
Option	Purpose
--dry-run=server	test on server without creating
--validate=true	validate YAML schema
Example output:
deployment created (server dry-run)
________________________________________
Comparing Changes
Use:
oc diff -f deployment.yaml
Purpose:
Compare live resource vs manifest.
Example output:
- image: nginx:v1
+ image: nginx:latest
Meaning:
Image will change.
This is useful in GitOps workflows.
________________________________________
Restarting Pods After Config Changes
Example problem:
You update:
•	ConfigMap
•	Secret
Pods do not automatically restart.
Solution:
oc rollout restart deployment myapp
This recreates pods.
________________________________________
Patching Resources
Sometimes you want to modify small parts of a resource.
Use:
oc patch
________________________________________
Patch Example
Update CPU request.
oc patch deployment hello -p \
'{"spec":{"template":{"spec":{"containers":[{"name":"hello","resources":{"requests":{"cpu":"100m"}}}]}}}}'
Meaning:
Set CPU request to 100 millicores.
________________________________________
Patch Using File
Command:
oc patch deployment hello --patch-file volume.yaml
Example patch file:
spec:
  template:
    spec:
      volumes:
      - name: www
        persistentVolumeClaim:
          claimName: nginx-www
This mounts a Persistent Volume Claim.
________________________________________
Key Commands Summary
Command	Purpose
oc create deployment	create resource imperatively
oc apply -f	create/update resource declaratively
oc create -f	create resources from YAML
oc diff -f	compare manifest with live object
oc patch	modify existing object
oc rollout restart	restart pods
oc explain	view manifest field documentation
________________________________________
Example oc explain
Command:
oc explain deployment
Shows fields in deployment.
Deep explanation:
oc explain deployment.spec.template.spec
________________________________________
Real Production Workflow
Typical production workflow:
1️⃣ Write manifests
deployment.yaml
service.yaml
route.yaml
2️⃣ Store in Git
3️⃣ Validate
oc apply --dry-run=server
4️⃣ Compare
oc diff
5️⃣ Deploy
oc apply -f .
________________________________________
Final Concept Summary
Imperative:
oc create deployment
oc set env
oc expose
Declarative:
deployment.yaml
service.yaml
route.yaml
oc apply -f .
Declarative is preferred because:
•	reproducible
•	version controlled
•	GitOps friendly
•	easier updates

